            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <head>Commentary</head>
                <list type="witDetail">
                    <item n="1"><p>QENN- (OI <hi rend="italic">cenn</hi> `head'): ... QENILOCI (<hi rend="italic">Cellach</hi>) <ref type="bibliog"
                                target="#MCM1991"><bibl>(<author>McManus</author> 
                                    <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                        >103</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>. 
                       
                    </p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p>It is tempting to equate the name MAQI-AINIA with the goddess <hi rend="italic">Áine</hi> but, as 
                        <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991"><bibl><author>McManus</author> (<date when="1991"
                                >1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp">109, 115, 179 n. 47</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> points out, <q>if so
                                    AI must be an error for A as the first syllable does not contain the diphthong <hi rend="italic">ai</hi>
                                </q> and palatalisation is not written in ogham.</p></item>
                    <item n="2"><p>The retention of the -I in QENILOCI in combination with the loss of -S in MAQI-AINIA suggests dating this 
                        inscription to the <origDate notBefore="0500" notAfter="0550">first half of the sixth century</origDate> <ref type="bibliog"
                            target="#MCM1991"><bibl>(<author>McManus</author> 
                                <date when="1991">1991</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                                    >95, 97</biblScope></bibl>)</ref>.</p></item>
                </list>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="locations">
                <head>Locations</head>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Found</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="found">the stone was found at <hi rend ="italic"><placeName type="sitename">Teampall Geal</placeName></hi> early ecclesiastical site in the townland of
                                <placeName type="townland">Ballymorereagh</placeName> and barony of
                            <placeName type="barony">Corkaguiney</placeName>. (GPS coordinates <geo>-10.331399, 52.154449</geo>)</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Original</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="origLocation">Find location possibly original site</rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
                <div type="history" n="locations">
                    <head>Last Recorded</head>
                    <p>
                        <rs type="lastLocation">In front of the oratory at <hi rend ="italic">Teampall Geal</hi>, secured within a metal fence and standing on a platform of concrete <ref
                            target="http://webgis.archaeology.ie/HistoricEnvironment/?SMRS=KE043-140008-"
                                >National Monuments Service Historic Environment viewer on
                            www.archaeology.ie</ref>. </rs>
                    </p>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="history" n="record">
                <head>History of Recording</head>
                <p><ref type="bibliog" target="#MAC1945"
                                ><bibl><author>Macalister</author> 
                            (<date when="1945">1945</date>, <biblScope type="pp"
                            >163</biblScope></bibl>)</ref> cites Petrie (1845, 136) as the first recording of the stone.</p>
            </div>
